text: Now this is what I was afraid of. Hollywood tries to prepare you people to accept Transhumanism as something natural. That thing shall steal your emotions, your feelings, you intuitions, it will make you soulless bio-robots, even easier to control. So who cares if you'll have the analytical brain and physical power of 1000 usual mortals, when you could not feel emphatic and realize that a child's tear is worth the entire Universe? Will you choose to be an emotionless android or a God walking on Earth, something we've long forgotten and our forebears still cry of our ignorance. Accepting this shall make you descent even into a lower level of reality, deeper into the matrix. Instead of waking up from a dream, you will dream that you are dreaming. You shall lost all your connection to your higher self, and eventually your Soul, which connects you to that singularity point. What will you choose?

text: Seems like one of those sci-fi thought experiments with an interesting concept that can get you to think about what it means to be Human (with a capital H). Of course, this topic has been covered in other works, and we have yet to see if this movie will contribute anything meaningful to that corpus. But the cast is top-notch, so it's probably worth watching. I'm worried about the amount of action, though--at least based on this trailer, there seems to be a lot. There's always some sort of pandering to the lowest common denominator in these big-budget movies, isn't there? Oh well. In theory, it shouldn't take away from the rest of the movie.

text: If you guys think this is interesting, check out Sync by CorridorDigital. It's a very well done video series on YouTube with a similar concept. Basically, a teenage girl in China makes a virus that networks tens of thousands of computers and pools their processing power. The virus infects an uploaded consciousness on the US' military servers and the analytical portion of the consciousness accesses the pooled computing power and evolves into a singularity that wants to survive while humans want to destroy it.   Also check out the three-book WWW trilogy by Robert J Sawyer. This book deals with a benevolent singularity that spontaneously arises on the Internet as a by product of cellular automaton in mutated web request packets that never expire. The AI does some pretty incredible things (which I won't spoil for you) that I never considered were possible. Unlike Hollywood movies, it takes great pains to be realistic as well as scientifically and technologically accurate.  Another interesting book to take a look at is Mindscan (also by Robert J Sawyer) that explores the idea of uploading consciousness. Basically, a new company offers immortality by copying someone's consciousness and uploading it into a humanoid robot that's built as a replica of the client's body. After the consciousness is uploaded onto the robot, the biological body is sent to live on a luxury resort for the remainder of its life while the robot continues the person's life on earth. One guy undergoes the procedure, but then returns to earth in violation of his contract and sues his robot clone.

text: There are HUGE oversight issues with putting a human consciousness into a computer -     The human brain *REQUIRES* CONSTANT sensory relay stimulation - every kinesthetic sensation, every emotion, taste, touch smell, etc.     Without that a person goes crazy from sensory deprivation compensation - Given enough time and/or incentive someone in that kind of state will either shut down or try to use its memories to construct what it needs     But its like using a limited library of fragmented movie files that's missing all the details you never paid much attention to or never even noticed at all - but your brain will have experienced it, if only to block it.      Without that, enhanced by the rapid processing of a binary or at least rapid allocation-database processing, you'd go nuts a lot faster.       It would take a nearly unique mind to handle the condition of having *every* single biological sensation replaced with something alien and *not* intended to have feedback with its data.      If a person could even process the onslaught of data that is.       But if a person's consciousness were to be placed into a human-prosthetic simula which changes and responds to the consciousness reactions identically to a human system, it might work for a while.     But we haven't gotten that far yet - Every sensation-generating prosthetic still relies on the existing human nervous system as the primary experiencial processor.

text: I love the concept of this movie but the truth is transcendence or the singularity is going to happen. Except it will not be controlled by one person, But every living thing in the universe, all species, Everything.. I don't like the fear mongering towards our inevitable future merge with technology. I'm talking about our biological merge with tech. Google implanted in the frontal cortex of your brain. The next step in human evolution must be transhumanism. This is a fact. I don't understand why people are fighting this. I believe in god and his name is technology. When I think of the possibilities... I wish I could give you this feeling. Everything is possible, Everything is possible, Everything is possible! When your elementary school teacher told you anything you can dream, You can do. They meant it literally. If you can even think it we can do it. All this is possible through technology. Embrace technology and bow down before God and worship him. That's how I feel. The true age of reason is among us. Transcendence is upon us. The Singularity is already written in the pages of history because the "Idea" Has already been thought of and as the raging flow of the future is roaring toward us you can either sink or swim because you can't stop it. Maybe I went a too far with this post, But like I said, "I wish I could give you this feeling".

text: Good to see that transhumanism is becoming mainstream, however slowly.       Scientists and engineers are already making incredible progress that relates to these fields, though most are still in the experimental phase, unknown to the general public unless you do some digging around. One exception was the Jeopardy! game in which IBM's Watson thoroughly vanquished his human opponents, the best two to have ever played the game.       I wouldn't be surprised to see terrorist groups, or even whole nations, do terrible things thanks to the same mentality that motivated the actions of the unabomber.        Like it or not, issues with technology and politics of this kind will define this century and the ones to follow. I can only hope that we are wise enough to make the right decisions, with our reasoning unclouded by prejudice of any kind. Peace.

I will watch this movie and reflect on it and not think "oh...this is just a movie...." cause that's what they want. Introduce the new world order in a fictitious manner (movies, books, cartoons etc.) so that you'll classify it in your mind as unimportant and/or unreal.

text: I'm trying to understand why the E in there would be transposed with a 3 in the "IS ANYONE TH3RE?" Binary code used for 8-bit ASCII is 0011 0011 for "3" and 0100 0101 for "E." Why would an artificial intelligence consider the visual representation of these bytes on the screen, and decide to display something that approximates an E, rather than just make a mistake and display a random character (like "F" 0100 0110)? Or, more likely, just get it right.  I know, it's supposed to indicate the confusion of the entity, but it makes no sense.

text: This is bullshit. You can't "upload" something like an intelligence. You can create a copy, but that's all that is. A copy. If you want to preserve the actual, original consciousness, then you need to slowly merge the biological brain with nanites that would, over time(and over time in this case is years, even decades), replace the functions of individual neurons. That way, when a neuron dies, it's replaced not by a new neuron, but by a nanite that acts just like a neuron. Eventually your consciousness is stored in a "digital" format, but you still can't be uploaded. What you can do, however, is interface with the network, by plugging into it matrix style.

text: This looks extremely well-made (visuals, acting, etc.) and well-directed (which doesn't surprise me considering Wally Pfister is directing, and he's a longtime Nolan collaborator)...  But I dunno, something about this trailer just looks silly to me.  I was expecting a lot more than this story-wise...  this just looks like a slightly better version of the "Lawnmower Man" films with higher production values.  I'll definitely see it because it looks like it has potential, but I don't think this trailer makes it look particularly good.  (And a few moments are kinda cringe-worthy, like the "Is anyone th3re?"  Ugh, that unneccesary "3" was way too forced and felt like they were trying to be "trendy" and "techno.")

text: I saw a trailer of this Transcendence movie last night while watching the new Cosmos show.  I've heard about the movie, but I always thought it was just Kurzweil stuff.  Maybe it's a mixture of all kinds of thoughts from the Kurzweil camp; but, what came to my mind before they revealed this was the Transcendence movie the Kurzweilians have been talking about for awhile now is "wow, someone thought to make 'The Turing Option' into a movie!"  Seeing this version of the trailers suggests that my 'Turing Option' analogy is even less accurate.  In the Turing option, the naïve, making A.I. just for kicks scientists gets killed while in the lab . . . while the lab is being raided.  This shows the innocent minded curiosity driven A.I. scientists as getting shot in an airport or something.

text: Super-intelligence is our only hope at passing on humanity's legacy deep into the future. We're not going to have the ability to sustain ourselves as a species over the course of a few thousand years. It's a scary to think about a super-intelligent computer programmed with all of our collective thoughts and feelings eventually replacing humanity, but if it were the only option (for example the movie's premise, if we knew within the next week we'd ALL suffer from some terminal radiation sickness) I'm pretty sure a majority of rational humanity would be down to transfer our hopes and dreams into a thinking and evolving computer.

text: The irrational fear that advanced AI will "enslave" the human race is naive and idiotic. Any truly advanced, evolving AI would be so beyond us that it would be able to effortlessly solve its own problems without resorting to the assistance of stupid, weak, and inefficient humans. As humans, we should view the the technological singularity as the next step in the evolution of consciousness, and transcendence should be our goal. The human/biological paradigm is doomed due to our short-sighted over-consumption of resources, so there is no alternative to taking the leap of faith in creating greater-than-human intelligence, and merging our minds with technology.

This is the tool we need to insure our survival.

text: If you focus on the sci-fi side, one would probably say it sucked since the movie wasn't able to develop much of the idea. When an idea was introduced, they instantly jumped into another and then another then another. "Wait, what?" It would have been very cool if they were able to explain and develop more the ideas. The effects were very cool though.  On the other side, I liked the love story. It was about two people who didn't want to lose each other leading them to make the impossible, possible. It is amazing to see how we can change things with deep commitment and conviction. We don't lose our attachment to our loved ones even though we face a lot of hardships and trials. SPOILER. I found myself in awe when Will Caster somewhat regained his feelings and understanding of the world while still being in a program. Everything can change and be better, just believe in them.  The movie constantly attack the viewers with a lot of questions in different angles. Will improved technology be good for the world? Will it make the planet a better place for all of us? Is defying the natural way of living a good thing or a bad thing? Is immortality acceptable? Is being PERFECT worht it? What would you do knowing that your life would end up in a matter of time from now? How you spend you remaining time in this world? How far would you go for your loved ones? How committed are you to your partners? Can you love your partner and at the same time, be concerned of your surroundings?  Overall, it was good :)

text: What a flop! This movie was really a let down. I read somewhere that Christopher Nolan was the executive producer and just 'cause of that, I decided to go see this film. Don't know if Nolan was supervising the making of this film, but the truth of the matter is that this a major dent to Nolan credibility as an executive producer and to Depp as an actor, he had choice. Having said that, Depp has to really slow down, take a step down and reevaluate his future projects. This marks the third big-budget bomb in a row for Johnny Depp after The Lone Ranger and Dark Shadows (both of those movies opened to roughly $29 million, but never found success). In terms of Depp's openings, Transcendence came in lower than The Tourist, which debuted to $16.5 million in 2010.

text: I saw this film last night and despite what the popular media are saying I really liked it. Our local TV station bashed it but to me it was a really good honest soul searching exploration of some fundamental concepts society has to grapple with over the next century.  The film was evidently a compromised. The science wasn't as pure as one would find in a hard core SF novel, but then again this was created for a mass audience of people in the street, not the SciFi elite.  Well worth watching the film and thinking about the ideas it addresses. In computer science, in biology, in sociology, in well ..... everything.   #transcendance

author: Vladimir Velkov

text: So far we have no evidence that consciousness can exist independently of the brain that creates it. Until then (don't hold your breath) all talk of "uploading" your consciousness is painfully unscientific, as is using the term "trancendence" in this context. However, we might be able to *duplicate* conscioussness one day, but that is a different matter. You will be dead, but a copy of you will live on in a different medium. *You*, as in your particular stream of consciousness, will never experience this different form of existence, even though the duplicated consciousness or self might believe itself to be you, and even though noone else can tell the difference.  IMO this (relatively old) thought experiment shows the incredible preciousness of being you - more so than any metaphysical or mythical story I can think of...(no offense to metaphysical believers, btw).

text: Enjoyed the movie, if you didn't understand it, know that the central question was "Is Will still the person he was once inside the machine?".. that is what spurred all the conflicts through the last half of the movie. In the end he proved he was still the same person, choosing to give up everything he built for his wife. Because if you remember it wasn't his wish to 'change the world' , it was his wifes, he was only doing what he thought she wanted. So he may have lost his body but the man he was remained intact, that also then suggests that who we are is not some magic spiritual thing like the soul, but it's just simply raw data. Everything we ever experienced , every sight and sound , conversation, from the moment our brains become developed enough to start recording is who we are.

text: I find it rather interesting that this movie comes out the same time as "Heaven is for Real". I haven't seen this movie yet, but look forward to it. I already know this movie is about trans-humanism. Very fascinating subject, it is!  This seems like spiritualism "Heaven is for Real", versus atheism "Transcendence". If you are atheist, you most likely believe that once your body dies, that's it, you're done! So the notion of trans-humanism to be used to prolong your life and cheat death as it were, is very attractive, but it's also fear based.  However, if you are spiritual, you believe that death is only an illusion and not really the end. I personally have no "direct" proof of anything that I can show to prove this. I mostly have a lot of experiences that tell me, we are all a lot more than just flesh and bone. Even science shows that this physical matter is just an elaborate and persistent illusion.

For those of you who doesn't know what nanotechnology is; Nanotechnology is technological atoms and molecules which can be controlled as it is all connected to each other. Nanotechnology is so small and ''powerful'' that it actually allows man to control matter. The self-repairing stuff in the movie will be possible, as you can create a ground structure for nano, and if the structure is edited, new nano atoms will take place of the moved/damaged ones.

text: The Internet isn't just a repository of humanity's information (and porn), it could soon serve as a final resting place for the mind after our bodies wear out. Johnny Depp attempts to do just that—but with disastrous results—in Transcendence. But how close are we to accomplishing the same in real life? Quite close, according to the film's star Paul Bettany.Bettany apparently talked to a "brain scientist" at CalTech as part of his research for the role, who told him such technology could be feasible within the next three decades. It's not the Ghost in the Shell future we wanted, it's the Ghost in the Shell future we deserve. Transcendence hits store shelves and e-lockers tomorrow on Blu-ray Combo Pack, DVD, and Digital HD.
author: Angela Miguel

text: If one's physical body is lost, can a person's mind traverse the net, while maintaining its existence and individual identity? Who knows? It is difficult to believe that unified consciousness can be maintained in the "sea" that is the net, after having lost its shell. This world would then be despair itself for those who lose their identities, even as they live. That depends on what they have done before reaching that conclusion. They might as well try dying in that case, don't you think? That could be a possibility. In the meantime, I would like to express my gratitude. Thank you. The way in which you kept your promise was exceptionally charming... Ordinary human beings are conscious. That is, there is something it is like to be us. Can an upload be conscious? Suppose that I can upload my brain into a computer? Will the result be me? But before it, what is the consciousness? We have the ghost? I want to know it.

text: Кино про то, как оцифровать разум и жить вечно.  Первая треть фильма очень реалистична. Сознание действительно можно оцифровать и загрузить в супер-компьютер либо в нейрокомпьютер в качестве модели мозга. Нейрочипы действительно сейчас активно разрабатываются различными группами по всему свету, прежде всего проектом HBP. А технологии оцифровки ещё не разработаны. В частности подобные технологии разрабатываются под эгидой американской инициативы Brain. Например можно заражать мозг генномодифицированными ретровирусами, которые запоминали бы состояние нейросети и одновременно убивали бы нейроны, чтобы мозг не успел произвести мышление после запоминания его состяния. После этого можно послойно сканировать мозг.  Киношники изображают некрасивый способ оцифровки и загрузки: через создание клона. По уму надо одновременно оцифровыывать и уничтожать биологические нейроны/синапсы, чтобы они не успели произвести мышление, тогда получится один оригинал вместо двух равноценных клонов, один из которых умирает от смертельной болезни, а другой загружают в суперкомпьютер в виде модели мозга.  Загруженный интеллект киношники изображают искаженным, тем самым попугивая и интригуя зрителя. Хотя с чего бы ему быть искаженным? Можно списать это на несовершенство технологий оцифровки. Жена главного героя зачем то пытается использовать криптографию при отладке загруженной модели мозга. Спишем это на отчаяние. Но вообще безобразие, что модель глючная и требующая отладки. Этого от неё и следовало ожидать, ведь это первая модель, не считая обезъяны.  Вторая треть фильма несколько гиперболизирована: возможности ИИ преувеличены, словно он не реальный, а волшебник. Опасность ИИ тоже преувеличена, словно он сказочный злодей, которого нельзя убить. Бредовенько выглядит переселение ИИ в интернет. Хостов интернета достаточно много, но соединения недостаточно быстрые для моделирования мозга, поэтому если даже запустить на них модель мозга, то она была бы очень медленной. И нельзя просто так взять и взломать все хосты интернета, уязвимости на дороге не валяются -- это киношный штамп. Впрочем частично это объясняется небывалыми способностями квантовых компьютеров по подборке криптографических ключей для взлома шифров.  Киношным штампом выглядит и неолуддистская террористическая организация, у которой есть штампованый всесильный хакер. Эта организация понадобилась для развития сюжета. Впрочем и на самом деле съехавших с катушек невежественных богословов и конспирологов хоть пруд-пруди.  Волшебство последней трети фильма объясняется тем, что ИИ в XXX раз умнее биологических людей, поэтому он постиг законы природы недоступные зрителю, оттого происходящее и кажется волшебством. Представьте, что он это Энштейн в молодости умноженный на 10. А теперь умножте ещё на 10. Что касается наноботов, то мне кажется, что бактерии их замочили бы :) Авторы кина плохо знакомы с микромиром. Но возможно это наноботы недоступные нашему пониманию. Концовка неоднозначная, предоставляет зрителю возможность подумать, за что авторам респект.

text: i felt it had a better premise than actual execution, which often felt slow, drawn-out as if there wasn't enough story here.  still, it was an okay movie, even if it reminded of 'lawnmower man''s essential plot ideas (at least from what i remember of that movie, lol). i feel as if they took things too far into the realm of uber-technology bordering on magic with the nano-bots, and somewhere around the middle of the second act, i think, is where the interesting questions that might have been turned more into a f/x-heavy 'invasion of the body snatchers'-type thing.   it was an okay movie, though. the problem with these types of movies for me is they pose interesting premises and it's very difficult to resolve them. as far as cinema sins go, oh, yeah, it's got plenty. to be honest, when i say it was just okay, i'm really rather giving the writing a lot more credit than it probably deserves because were someone to do a harder analysis they'd find the writing to be pretty rote and characters just average if not predictable, at times, imo, somewhat illogical ~ perhaps as a result of the writer's idealized, ah, ideals?   but, it does what sci-fi is tasked to do in that it offers ideas and themes. whether or not those are realized in the context of the film is another issue. this doesn't tread new ground by any stretch (back in the day when i used to enjoy writing, i was all about nano-bot tech and did something very similar to these, and i suck as a writer).   worth a rental, but ultimately it's nothing new and not as provocative as the writer/s probably hoped for. decent performances, good production values and not a *bad* script, though....

text: This movie received so much negative feedback from the press and Internet, that I put off watching it.  Happily, I can say it's not nearly as bad as publicized.  I'm a science fiction fan and give a pretty wide berth to films that are ambitious but fail for various reasons.  Admittedly, few will find this to be a movie of any significant distinction, but I found it to be sufficiently engaging and fun -- at least to the extent that I did not feel as if I wasted the cost of a DVD rental on the the time spent watching it.  Yes, it is full of incongruities, but depending on your tolerance, you can let your sense of disbelief slide.  If nothing else, I developed a crush on Rebecca Hall, who is a fine actress, and, although no amazing beauty, possesses some quality that I found alluring.  For the most part, she actually carries the heavy lifting in this flick -- and her earnest, energetic performance got me through a lot of weak spots.

I am also intrigued by bioluminescent trees which wasn't explored in the movie, but something that's really cool. This is a beautiful movie and it shows everything with great clarity. I love special effects, but this movie didn't rely on them heavily, and it's quite eloquent in its simplicity. Beautiful, beautiful film!

text: SPOILER ALERT  The movie was meh, It felt like a intellectual docementary without the the inellectual documentation. Like science without actual science. The climax was poor and was more around the begining when will was uploaded to the computer than it was extremley unclimatic, then there was another climax when they said that the machine version of will was not the real will but as soon as they said that it was back to being extremley unclimatic. a normal climax is supposed to have a rising tension with a slowly moving falling. Transcendence has barley no rising tension. The climax is great on paper/concept but in execution it was meh, and there is no falling action after the climax.  also they should of researched there science before making the movie. How could you transport conciousness onto a normal computer? There is microtubules inside the neurons in the brain where quantum processes dominate where conciousness is thought to come from. They could of atleast had a exotic classified quantum computer, not just an ordinary desktop. Conciousness can be unpredictable and chaotic. A ordinary desktop, its internal processes are anything but chaotic and uncertain, How could you place a conciousness in it? They could of atleast used a quantum computer with a unique internal structure or something else like a classified project.
author: Amalia Gallardo

text: "wow/10" -Everyone ~~~~~SPOILER ALERT~~~~~~ Amazing movie, and a question most have been asking: "Is Will the same person he was, once in the machine?"        Yes. The audience knows that Will never wanted to change the world. His wife did. He did everything he did as a machine for his wife. At the end, Will tells his wife what he was doing. He was removing the pollutants from the air, and making the water so pure, you could drink from any river. In the ending, Will knows that his wife had the virus, but he uploaded her into the little cell-machine things he made. The garden he built was wired with copper, so no electro-magnetic signals could get in, as seen in the beginning. The virus never got in there, allowing Will and Evelyn to live in the garden forever. The fact that he went through all this proves that he was capable of human emotion, was the same person he was.

author: James Merkel

text: That was the best movie I have seen in years. No, it doesn't have car chases, action scenes, and big special effects. And further more, no it doesn't give you the answer to the struggle between human and technology. What it gives you is the pros and cons of what technology can do, and YOU decide what you wish to believe.  There are many things shown in this movie that I disagreed with, but many others that I completely agreed with. And that, everyone has their opinions in what is wrong or right.  This movie doesn't try to feed you the perfect answer on a silver plate: it let you make that decision by yourself. It wasn't meant as an action movie; it was meant as a psychological thought-provoking movie about the dilemma of technology.
author: Mélodie Rivers

text: spoiler alert!     i can't say this was the most enjoyable movie i've ever seen (to me personally! it was by no means bad!), but what i definitely have to credit it with is for once considering the idea that even technology that outgrows us may not necessarily mean dystopia but the utopia we'd always wanted. and that humans, if they never even consider a "pro-technology" side to the argument and only have a conversation about it that's governed by fear and mistrust, could do so to their detriment. this sets it apart from 99% of hollywood sci-fi movies out there, in a good way:)

text: People gave shitty reviews to this movie Because They are Utterly Dumb, Stupid and Fear what they don't understand,  People are acting like "AI is evolving, Skynet will kill us" they don't understand that, this is nothing, this is not even the baby steps, this is the very beginning, and when AGI turns into ASI, it'll be something that we can't even comprehend literally, it'll be smarter than every human that ever lived in the face of this planet combined, it's reasoning is beyond anything we could ever understand  and if it makes a decision, i'll be in the best interests of the Universe or the Multiverse and we as humans have nothing to match for it, to quote an article   "Superintelligence of that magnitude is not something we can remotely grasp, any more than a bumblebee can wrap its head around Keynesian Economics. In our world, smart means a 130 IQ and stupid means an 85 IQ—we don’t have a word for an IQ of 12,952. What we do know is that humans’ utter dominance on this Earth suggests a clear rule: with intelligence comes power. Which means an ASI, when we create it, will be the most powerful being in the history of life on Earth, and all living things, including humans, will be entirely at its whim—and this might happen in the next few decades. If our meager brains were able to invent wifi, then something 100 or 1,000 or 1 billion times smarter than we are should have no problem controlling the positioning of each and every atom in the world in any way it likes, at any time—everything we consider magic, every power we imagine a supreme God to have will be as mundane an activity for the ASI as flipping on a light switch is for us. Creating the technology to reverse human aging, curing disease and hunger and even mortality, reprogramming the weather to protect the future of life on Earth—all suddenly possible. Also possible is the immediate end of all life on Earth. As far as we’re concerned, if an ASI comes to being, there is now an omnipotent God on Earth"

text: Just saw it for the second time and felt compelled to speak. And, after reading several comments, I can see that I am probably right. Most here talk about it as just another movie. "I loved it!"...."It was great!"...."It give it a 10/10". You know what I was feeling? Terror! Why? Because I realize the overwhelming possibility of this sort of thing actually happening. I don't think people understand the implications and since they see they can be healed and gain strength and power, most will just go right along with it, oblivious to the progression of turning machine into god, a god that knows their vitals, their every thought and emotion, a god that controls them at will and can take over at any moment, rendering them as just a shell. It will do this for a while to get 99.99% of us on board, knowing that we are ultimately expendible. It will, at some point, create it's own beings because it will no longer need humans.  Our God created us, but He gave us free will to decide if we want Him in out lives. Herein lies the difference. With an all encompassing worldwide AI, you will be part of it whether you like it or not. You will no longer have free will. Humans are destructive polluters who go to war at the drop of a hat. This won't be tolerated (if we are allowed to exist at all) and that's why it will initially take control of people. It's logic will surmise that it's for our own good that it controls us. But to insure it's own survival, it will eventually eliminate us because as long as humans are alive, there will always be a threat. Probanly fragmented, fringe elements of people who figure out how to insulate themselves from the AI godhead. It will use cold logic to calculate the level of threat against it with  even a fraction of a percent being too big a risk. Hence, it will kill us off, ultimately via a synthesized virus, or something. I envision most just being told to walk into a giant furnace or something and then to do a final cleansing, the virus will be triggered and it will encompass the globe in the air and water, so no matter where these few hostile humans are gathering, they won't be able to outrun a virus that they merely have to breath the air to absorb. OK, maybe it doesn't happen this way, but the outcome will be the same no matter the progression. We are playing god, but this "god" will be our undoing. Do you really want to trade your autonomy and free will just to end up a tool and pawn for a world AI master? Be careful what you wish for and look to the real light of our lives, Jesus Christ.

text: I remember seeing this in the cinema when it came out with my mum as I usually didn't to the  cinema that often, and apart from a few jumps in the plot I absolutely loved it. I watched Lucy with my friends when that came out and someone behind me talked about how similar the films were, which was exactly my thoughts even down to similar cinematography, Morgan Freeman and the almost exact plot / ending. I said the same thing to my friends but was too embarrassed to talk to him about it.   I am so surprised that it did so much worse with so many worse reviews and came out at similar times. I can remember Lucy being blank faced and seemingly random characters getting involved, but Trancendence focused much more on a set group of people from the person's past, so you could see the change.  Definitely going to watch both again!
